    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i've been trying to do the three-coat method but i keep seeing these tiny little pits and small cracks appearing in the mud even after it dries. it's like things are getting trapped in there or something. how do i make sure the surface is actually solid and smooth before i start the final sanding?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The pits and cracks you're seeing are usually signs that the mud isn't fully cured or that you've rushed the process. You need to let each coat dry *properly*, which is crucial. If you're seeing those imperfections, it's often because the previous coat wasn't fully set before you applied the next layer.\n\nBefore you even think about sanding, you need to make sure the surface is rock solid. You can try lightly sanding the dried mud with a very fine-grit sandpaper—like 220 or higher—just to knock down any raised edges or soft spots. Don't go heavy; you're just trying to smooth the surface, not remove the material. If you see anything that looks loose, you might need to spot-fill it with a little more mud and let it cure again.",
      "source": "target",
