    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "yeah i'll try the finer grit. also, i was looking at the space behind the wall where the plumbing goes in, and i noticed some weird gaps in the framing and some irregular holes near the floor level. is that something i should worry about for the drywall, or is it just normal stuff from the build?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Gaps and irregular holes behind the wall framing, especially near the floor, are often just the way the old construction settled, or maybe some forgotten plumbing chases. Don't let those minor structural quirks turn you into a nervous wreck, though. If those gaps are wide and look like they could compromise the structure, then you'd want to call in a structural expert, but for drywall patching, it's usually just a bit of messy work.\n\nJust be careful when you're taping over those areas; if you see a significant void, you might need to use a thicker mud or even some specialized patching compound to fill those irregular holes before you start your final finish coats. Keep an eye out for any signs of water damage or active leaks, though.",
